metrics_conclusion: In terms of chords and melody, Terraria Calamity Mod - Murderswarm is more complex than the typical song, having above average scores in Chord Complexity, Melodic Complexity, Chord Progression Novelty and Chord-Bass Melody.
key_conclusion: Terraria Calamity Mod - Murderswarm has sections analyzed in the following keys: G Minor, C Minor,  and E Phrygian.  Click on the linked cheat sheets for popular chords, chord progressions, downloadable midi files and more!

metadata.editComments:
Removed pickup melody for the verse.

(another fun fact about this section: this is literally just the "Yharon motif" stretched out to groove in 3x 7/8 + 9/8 time: same melodic contour, same notes even. Compare this to the verse of "Infernal Catharsis". As I mentioned before, this is no coincidence.)

Added pickup measure to better transition from the previous section. (going to edit intro again later)
More lore(tm) time:
This section is, as I might(n't) have mentioned, very similar to the verse of "Infernal Catharsis". The key(s) are the same (Cm-F#m, here it's a key change); half of this section's melody is an altered "Yharon motif" (the 1-4-b7-6-b7-6-4 thing) that drops the 1-4-b7 jump for an embellished 5-b3-1-b7; the i7 - vi7-bVI7 chord progression shows up in both songs; the rhythm is similar (4/4 + 7/8 here and 6/4 there); even the funky tritone jump's here! (here it's a full-on key change).
As I mentioned in the intro, this is no coincidence. Before v2.0.2 "From the Ashes", and probably even when he was still the "Bumblebirb", the Dragonfolly was a botched clone of Yharon. The composer, DM DOKURO, did a great job implementing leitmotifs here, as like how the Bumblebirb used to be a spoof of Yharon, "Murderswarm" is a spoof of "Infernal Catharsis." Neat.

Changed seventh chords to basic triads, and changed mode in last 4 bars to A minor.

This is a major tone shift from the previous section, both literally and figuratively: we've changed keys a WHOLE step down from F#m to Em, and instead of a slow prog rock-pop-ish melody ambling around chromatic chords we've now doubled the tempo and started leaning full into a more "metal" style. As mentioned before, this is no coincidence: have a listen to the pre-chorus of "Infernal Catharsis," it's extremely similar to this in structure.
Gameplay-wise, this ramp-up in intensity might mirror the charges and "red lightning" the Dragonfolly keeps spewing out at you (Maybe, I don't know, I don't think I've ever actually beaten the Dragonfolly on-tier as intended, even when it was still the "Bumblebirb"), with the buzzing synth line resembling an angry bee-dragon-thing, and the guitars portraying the heat of the moment?? (never been good at thematic analysis)
Changed i7 to i7sus4 and shortened piano notes
